## Scenario 3: Replace UI Design Completely

**The change:** You hire a designer and want to restyle every page — new colors, new layout, new component library (e.g., switching from shadcn to Material UI, or going fully custom).

---

### Difficulty by page

| Page | Difficulty | Why |
|------|-----------|-----|
| [Landing.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/Landing.jsx) | 🟢 Easy | Clean structure. Business logic (fetch, filter) is clearly separate from layout JSX. |
| [Admin.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/Admin.jsx) | 🟡 Medium | Layout is clean, but the optimistic delete+undo logic (lines 62-98) is woven into the component. You'd have to preserve that logic while rebuilding the UI. |
| [Profile.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/Profile.jsx) | 🟡 Medium | 427 lines. Avatar upload handler, username debounce checker, form state — all live in the same component as the JSX. Restyling means working around 200 lines of inline business logic. |
| [Auth.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/Auth.jsx) | 🔴 Hard | **600 lines. 300 of which are a self-contained CSS string.** This page uses an entirely separate styling system (hardcoded pixel values, hex colors, custom class names). You can't restyle this by changing Tailwind tokens — you'd need to tear out the inline CSS and rewrite the entire component. |
| [CompleteProfile.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/CompleteProfile.jsx) | 🔴 Hard | Same problem as Auth — 90 lines of injected CSS, its own design language, hardcoded colors. |
| [PublicVault.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/PublicVault.jsx) | 🟡 Medium | Clean layout, but inline Supabase queries and bulk-add logic live inside the component. |
| [SharedVault.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/SharedVault.jsx) | 🟡 Medium | Near-identical structure to PublicVault. These two share ~70% of the same code and should have been a shared component with different data sources. |
| [PromptCard.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/components/PromptCard.jsx) | 🔴 Hard | This is the single most important visual component and also the most tangled. Redesigning this card means carefully preserving clipboard logic, usage tracking, selection mode, vault-adding, route detection, and framer-motion animations — all of which are interleaved with the layout code. |

### Where architecture fails during a redesign

**1. Business logic is embedded in presentation components**

A well-structured app lets you rip out all JSX and replace it without touching any logic. Your app doesn't allow that. Here's what's tangled in page components:

```
Profile.jsx (427 lines)
├── Username availability checking (lines 69-112) → business logic
├── Image upload + WebP conversion (lines 115-179) → business logic  
├── Form validation (lines 183-212) → business logic
├── Avatar upload to Supabase Storage → data layer
├── Direct Supabase query for username check → data layer
└── JSX layout (lines 222-424) → presentation
```

To restyle Profile, you'd need to understand and preserve all of the above while replacing the JSX. If you touch the wrong line, username validation or avatar upload breaks.

**Contrast with the ideal:**
```
useProfileForm() hook → all logic
ProfilePage component → pure JSX that calls the hook
```

**2. Two pages that resist redesigning**

Auth.jsx and CompleteProfile.jsx are essentially standalone HTML/CSS pages pasted into React. They don't use your design system at all. Redesigning them isn't "change these Tailwind classes" — it's "rewrite these 600-line components from scratch."

**3. SharedVault and PublicVault are copy-pasted siblings**

These two pages share: the same header layout, the same search bar, the same prompt grid, the same bulk-add footer, the same selection mode logic (identically coded). But they're two completely separate 250-line files. A redesign means doing the same visual work twice and keeping them visually in sync manually.

**4. No component library abstraction**

You import shadcn/Radix components directly:
```
@radix-ui/react-dialog
@radix-ui/react-dropdown-menu
@radix-ui/react-toast
... (20+ Radix packages)
```

But the main pages barely use them. Landing, Admin, Profile — they're all raw `<input>`, `<button>`, `<div>` with Tailwind classes. The 20+ Radix dependencies in package.json are mostly unused weight. If you wanted to swap to a different component library, you'd need to audit which Radix components are actually used (likely just Toast and maybe Dialog).

### Difficulty: 🟠 Hard overall

**Landing page? Easy. Auth page? Rewrite from scratch. PromptCard? Surgery.**

The core issue: **no custom hooks extracting logic from pages**. Your entire app has exactly **2 custom hooks** (`usePlan` and `use-mobile`). A codebase this size should have 8-10 — one per major page — separating data fetching and business logic from layout.

